## **Understanding Data Needs**

- What types of data does the ML model require? (e.g., image formats, resolution, labels, metadata)  
  - [https://www.cloudfactory.com/training-data-guide](https://www.cloudfactory.com/training-data-guide)  
  - Labeled data is easier to process, especially for images.  
    - Labelled data \= data manually tagged for the model to learn from  
    - Each label needs weight/scoring applied to it  
- What are the key features that must be extracted from raw images to train the model effectively?  
  - Patterns, textures, colors, shapes, edges, etc.  
  - [https://www.cloudfactory.com/training-data-guide](https://www.cloudfactory.com/training-data-guide)   
- How much data is required to achieve meaningful model performance?  
  - [https://postindustria.com/how-much-data-is-required-for-machine-learning/](https://postindustria.com/how-much-data-is-required-for-machine-learning/)   
  - Also depends on range of error, features that need to be accounted for  
    - “10 times rule,” The amount of input data should be at least 10 times more than the number of degrees of freedom of a model (parameters) (mostly useful for a rough estimate)  
  - Range from couple hundred to tens of thousands, depends on how complicated the model is.

# Data Acquisition

Some questions that we should be asking ourselves when we choose what kind of tools we are using for live image processing includes:

- What types of image or video inputs are supported (e.g., camera feeds, image sequences, video files, streaming protocols)?  
- What formats can the tool generate or export (e.g., processed video, annotated frames, data overlays, feature maps)?  
- Specifications and capabilities?  
- What processing capabilities does the tool offer?  
- Are there limitations on resolution, frame rate, or color depth?  
- Are there APIs or SDKs available for customization and integration?

## OpenCV

What: 

* Windows bitmaps: `.bmp`, `.dib` (always supported)  
* JPEG files: `.jpeg`, `.jpg`, `.jpe`  
* JPEG 2000 files: `.jp2`  
* Portable Network Graphics: `.png`  
* WebP: `.webp`  
* Portable image format: `.pbm`, `.pgm`, `.ppm`, `.pxm`, `.pnm` (always supported)  
* Sun rasters: `.sr`, `.ras` (always supported)  
* TIFF files: `.tiff`, `.tif`  
* OpenEXR Image files: `.exr`  
* Radiance HDR: `.hdr`, `.pic` (always supported)

## Pillow

Can’t take in video formats like MP4, AVI, or MOV directly, for actual video processing, other libraries recommended, so probably can’t use it by itself.

* Can work it in with OpenCV, imageio, or MoviePy to extract individual frames while Pillow image objects.  
* Overall thing seems to be that it should be complemented with libraries like OpenCV or scikit-image  
* But it seems to be good for manipulating, image enhancement, filtering, color space conversion, and pixel-level operations.  
* Specs: Cross-platform (windows, linux, macOS), designed fo fast access to pixel data.

Types of data it can accept:  
Fully Supported (Read/Write): JPEG, PNG, BMP, GIF, TIFF, WebP, AVIF, ICNS, ICO, PCX, PPM, SGI, TGA, XBM.  
Read- Only: Photoshop files, FITS, FLI/FLC, MPO, PCD, WMF  
Write-only: PDF, Palm

Output to Other Data Types: NumPy Arrays, Byte Buffers/Strings

Output File Formats: JPEG, PNG, TIFF, GIF, BMP, PDF, WebP, AVIF, DDS, SGI, TGA

Format Size Limits

* ICO: MAx size is 256 \* 256  
* WebP: 16383 \* 16383 

[https://pillow.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html](https://pillow.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html)

## FFmpeg (and its libraries)

FFmpeg isn’t specifically a “vision” library but a media toolkit: decode/encode many formats, handle streaming, containers, protocols. Useful for ingesting live camera streams, converting formats, streaming out processed frames. 

- Local files: .mp4, .avi, .mkv, .mov, .flv, .mxf, etc.  
- Raw image sequences: .jpg, .png, .bmp, .tiff, etc.  
- Streaming inputs: RTSP, RTMP, HLS, MPEG-TS, SRT, WebRTC (via integrations)  
- Live camera feeds: USB webcams, IP cameras, capture cards, system devices (/dev/video\* on Linux, dshow on Windows)

FFmpeg is effectively “format-agnostic”—if a format exists, FFmpeg can likely read it.  
 It’s also capable of handling **multi-stream and multi-source input** for advanced workflows.

While FFmpeg is not a full computer vision framework like OpenCV, it provides a rich set of built-in filters and transformations that can be applied to live or recorded video streams. Examples:

- Image and video transformations: crop, resize, rotate, flip, scale  
- Color space conversion: RGB ↔ YUV, grayscale, thresholding  
- Filtering: blurring, sharpening, denoising  
- Compositing: overlaying text, logos, or watermarks  
- Frame rate adjustments: upsampling/downsampling frames  
- Edge detection and motion estimation (basic)  
- Split/Merge streams: e.g., process multiple camera feeds simultaneously  
- Frame-by-frame output for external ML inference 

Downside: The API has a learning curve; debugging can be complex compared to higher-level frameworks.

## VidGear

VidGear is a Python video-processing framework built on top of FFmpeg, OpenCV, etc. It supports real-time processing, frame-by-frame access, streaming, network transfers. [GitHub+1](https://github.com/abhiTronix/vidgear?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* Best if you are working in Python and want a higher-level API for grabbing frames, streaming, chunking, etc.  
* Consider: for very high performance or very high resolution you may need to drop down a level or use GPU acceleration.

Summary: VidGear is a High-Performance Video Processing Python Library that provides a Multi-Threaded \+ Asyncio API Framework on top of specialized libraries like OpenCV, FFmpeg, ZeroMQ, picamera2, starlette, yt\_dlp, pyscreenshot, dxcam, aiortc and python-mss serving at its backend, and enable us to use their internal parameters and methods, while error-handling and real-time performance. VidGear primarily focuses on simplicity, and thereby lets programmers and software developers to easily integrate and perform Complex Video Processing Tasks, in just a few lines of code.

## Py-Torch

Used in research and industry for image classification, object detection, and feature extraction  
Let's you:

* Design and train convolutional neural networks (CNNs)  
* Import pre-trained models (like ResNet, VGG, MobileNet)  
* Fine-tune models on your own dataset of images or videos

Some limitations are

* Can be slow or inefficient without a GPU  
* Memory usage can be high, challenging to achieve real-time performance without converting or optimizing the model for the target hardware   
* Installation and setup can also be complex, especially when configuring dependencies on embedded systems 

## TorchVision:

(Toolkit that works like a supportive companion library to PyTorch)  
Input/output: same as TensorFlow  
Benefits: 

- Has access to Pre-trained Models for transfer learning

Limitations: 

- Input/Output are primarily optimized for offline data loading  
  - Not designed for direct, real-time, low-latency streaming protocols or camera interaction
